                                        OPERATER IN JAVASCRIPT.

In JavaScript, an operator is a special symbol used to perform operations on operands (values and variables). Operators are essential for manipulating data and variables in JavaScript. Here's a breakdown of the various types of operators in JavaScript:
1. Arithmetic Operators
Arithmetic operators are used to perform basic mathematical operations.
•	+ : Addition
•	- : Subtraction
•	* : Multiplication
•	/ : Division
•	% : Modulus (remainder)
•	** : Exponentiation (ES6)
let a = 10;
let b = 3;
console.log(a + b); // 13
console.log(a - b); // 7
console.log(a * b); // 30
console.log(a / b); // 3.3333333333333335
console.log(a % b); // 1
console.log(a ** b); // 1000
2. Assignment Operators
Assignment operators are used to assign values to variables.
•	= : Assign
•	+= : Add and assign
•	-= : Subtract and assign
•	*= : Multiply and assign
•	/= : Divide and assign
•	%= : Modulus and assign
let a = 5;
a += 2; // a = a + 2
console.log(a); // 7

3. Comparison Operators
Comparison operators are used to compare two values.
•	== : Equal to
•	!= : Not equal to
•	=== : Strict equal to
•	!== : Strict not equal to
•	> : Greater than
•	< : Less than
•	>= : Greater than or equal to
•	<= : Less than or equal to
let a = 10;
let b = '10';
console.log(a == b); // true
console.log(a === b); // false

4. Logical Operators
Logical operators are used to perform logical operations.
•	&& : Logical AND
•	|| : Logical OR
•	! : Logical NOT
let a = true;
let b = false;
console.log(a && b); // false
console.log(a || b); // true
console.log(!a); // false
5. Bitwise Operators
Bitwise operators are used to perform bit-level operations.
•	& : AND
•	| : OR
•	^ : XOR
•	~ : NOT
•	<< : Left shift
•	>> : Right shift
•	>>> : Zero-fill right shift
let a = 5; // 0101 in binary
let b = 3; // 0011 in binary
console.log(a & b); // 1 (0001 in binary)
console.log(a | b); // 7 (0111 in binary)
6. String Operators
String operators are used to concatenate strings.
•	+ : Concatenation
let str1 = 'Hello, ';
let str2 = 'world!';
console.log(str1 + str2); // Hello, world!
7. Ternary Operator
The ternary operator is a shorthand for the if statement.
•	? : : Conditional (ternary) operator
let age = 20;
let canVote = (age >= 18) ? 'Yes' : 'No';
console.log(canVote); // Yes
8. Type Operators
Type operators are used to check or change the type of a value.
•	typeof : Returns the type of a variable
•	instanceof : Checks if an object is an instance of a particular class or constructor function
let a = 42;
console.log(typeof a); // number
let b = 'Hello';
console.log(b instanceof String); // false




